Great game. Played Raiden Fighters Jet on arcade cabinets in the past, and still love the game. The games are ported over very well, with different control settings to map how quickly your ship moves, different difficulties and even a stage select. Having a shoot-em-up with your ship mapped to your finger is such a great idea and controls so intuitively that I have no idea why other publishers haven't ported over similar titles. My only dissapointment with this app is the lack of Raiden 2.

The game does not pause when you take your finger off the screen. That's a 
problem. The ship's defenses are terrible. You die way too quickly. Tons of 
bombs should be on hand, not the tiny amounts available. There is a delay 
when you slam on the bomb button. In game like this, you want to use bombs 
often and plentifully. I was about choose refund in the play store, but I 
think I'd rather keep it. I used to play one of Raidens in the arcade. Was 
tons of fun. This is semi fun. The games last update was in 2017. Today is 
August 7th 2018. The game is designed for a 16:9 screen aspect ratio. I 
have a Samsung Galaxy S9, which has an 18:9 screen aspect ratio. The game 
does not fill the screen. There are pillar bars at the top and bottom. 
Please fix as much for new generation screens asap. Lastly, writing this 
review was difficult. The sreen scrolled wrongfully. Was twitchy. Godspeed 
everyone.

I was never a huge fan of the Raiden series to be honest, but having exhausted the Cave shmups for Android I decided to give Raiden Legacy a go. If there had been a lite/free trial available for this game (so that I could test it out first), then I would not have bought it. My main issue was that Raiden does not have sharp & accurate controls. With other Android shmups (e.g. Dodonpachi, Xelorians etc), the ship accurately follows your finger (kind of clinging to your finger) wherever you go on the screen. With Raiden, the ship feels like it is connected to your finger by an invisible rubber band that catapults the ship all over the screen. This makes it incredibly difficult to accurately dodge bullets. I could only personally recommend this to hardcore Raiden fans.

Lots of fun and near perfect emu port!  I would recommend the following to make it perfect.  1. Bluetooth controller support.  All emulators do this and is the reason why all of us old school gamers love Mame.  Specifically support for idroid snakebyte controller.  2. Unlimited coins to continue (or have this as an option to separate purists from gamers).  All of these arcade games were designed to suck down your quarters and this is another reason why Mame is popular.   Thats it everything else is perfect and the game is well worth the price!   ******Bug Found*******  The sound effects and music inside Raiden are to the point where you can barely hear it, even when volume is all the way up.  After the game ends and brings you back to the title screen volume goes back to normal until you play again. No other games included have this problem.

I was recommended this by a friend who has it on his iPad, and low and behold there's an Android version. So I paid the measly ¬£3.50 for this game, and dang do you get a lot of bang for the buck! Most Bullet Hell style shooters on touch screen devices suffer from either bad controls, and/or over complicating things like switch weapons and so on. Raiden Legacy is ultra responsive, and keeps the game play simple by only providing 2 on screen buttons on the left hand side. One if you're using Auto fire. For an arcade port, I'd even say this is a billion times better than that Rtype port that was released a year or so a go. A definite thumbs up for DotEmu and Seibu Kaihatsu for such a great port of a great top down shooter...  Can't wait to play this on Ouya! :D

I haven't had many chances to play the Raiden games since when I had played them at the local pizza shop as a child.  Console versions of the Raiden games were scarcely released.  When I found out that DotEmu was releasing the Raiden games on Android, I jumped on the chance to play them.  I'm so glad I did!  The games run so buttery smooth on my Tegra 3 tablet.  And the games actually work on the ICade emulation function of my Nyko PlayPad Pro, a welcome feature at a time where every developer is jumping on the Moga bandwagon.  And with four games at a price of $5, it is an incredible value.  I highly recommend it!
